Roman roads and straight roads in the UK

Author
Affiliation

Peter EJ Kemp

King’s College London

Published

January 4, 2024

This is an interactive map of the known Roman roads across England, overlaid with extant roads that have names suggesting a roman origin, e.g. “straight road”, “roman road”, “the street”, “the causeway”. Whilst many roads with these names will be modern roads, some will be on the same routes as the Roman roads. This map allows you to explore the extent to which this is true.

Modern road data (in blue) for Bedfordshire, Berkshire, Buckinghamshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Cornwall, Cumbria, Devon, Dorset, Durham, East Sussex, Essex, Hampshire, Hertfordshire, Kent, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Oxfordshire, Rutland, Somerset, Suffolk, Surrey, Warwickshire, West Sussex, Wiltshire from Open Street Map, matched by name including “(?i)the strait|straight lane|roman lane|straight lane|the street|roman road|straight road|the straight|streht”.

Roman roads (in red) from: http://romanroadsinbritain.info/data.html, copyright M.C.Bishop with a Creative Commons (Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike or CC BY-NC-SA) licence.
